}¬}\pard\tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\ql\qnatural
\cf0 \
\
\pard\tx565\tx1133\tx1700\tx2266\tx2832\tx3401\tx3967\tx4535\tx5102\tx5669\tx6235\tx6802\ql\qnatural
\cf0 Here, no contact-specific preferences have been set for signing or for which message format to use, so GPGMail will use it's global defaults. However, GPGMail has been explicitly requested to always encrypt emails to this contact (assuming that it can), overriding the global defaults.\
\
A preference is changed by pressing the normal card 'Edit' button. You can then select from the options available for each preference in it's popup menu. The "Mime Message Format" field allows you to select whether to use the default GPGMail preference for adding signature and encryption information to an email or whether to always force the use of the newer pgp/mime standard. If you work in a predominantly Outlook or Outlook Express environment, you may wish to set GPGMail to use the Inline message format by default and then 'upgrade' specific contacts to use the newer (but Outlook Express incompatible) pgp/mime format. Note that the Inline message format cannot cope with attachments so GPGMail will automatically convert any email with attachments to pgp/mime anyway.\
\
Turning off the GPGMail options fields will not delete custom preferences you may have set. You can turn the fields off in the Template preferences simply by clicking the red '-' symbol next to them (as you would for any other Address Book field). If you have turned off the GPGMail options fields, you can turn them on again by selecting the field from the drop-down list in the Template preferences pane or from the Card -> Add Field main menu.\
\
You can specify whether you wish the GPGMail options fields to show at the top or the bottom of the Contact's card in the ABKey preferences pane.\

